    "recommendations": [
      "Inside the per-entry loop (after path.json validates), read paths.join(slugDir, 'phases.json'), parse, run validatePhases. On read/parse/schema failure emit a structured warning ('missing-phases-json' | 'malformed-phases-json' | 'invalid-phases-json') and skip the entry, mirroring the path.json logic.",
      "After validatePath succeeds, assert validation.value.slug === entry.name; on mismatch emit a structured warning ('slug-dir-mismatch') with both values and skip the entry, OR canonicalize on entry.name and treat the path.json slug field as advisory.",
      "Replace existsSync with try/readFileSync; on ENOENT emit 'missing-path-json', on other errors emit a distinct 'unreadable-path-json' warning carrying the OS-level error message.",
      "In scanRegistry, after validatePath succeeds, also read paths/<slug>/phases.json and run validatePhases on it. On failure, push a structured warning (kind 'malformed-phases-json' / 'invalid-phases-json') and skip the path — same flow as path.json. This keeps the schemas module load-bearing and makes the registry the single chokepoint for path well-formedness.",
      "Add a registry test: construct a path with valid path.json but phases.json missing the phases array (or with a zero-spot phase), and assert (a) the path is omitted from result.paths and (b) result.warnings contains a phases-schema warning identifying the file. Either that, or amend the contract to declare phases.json validation out of scope for cycle 1's registry."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "The scanner reads and validates path.json only. The contract for registry.ts states it 'Skips non-directories, malformed JSON, schema-invalid files, and dirs missing path.json' — implying phases.json is part of what makes a path 'well-formed'. validatePhases() is exported and unit-tested directly (T-037..T-039), but the registry loop never calls it. A path dir with a valid path.json and a malformed or schema-invalid phases.json will surface as a healthy PathInfo with zero warnings.",
      "scanRegistry iterates directory entries by entry.name but emits PathInfo.slug from validation.value.slug (the value inside path.json). If a dir is named '01-orderbook-viewer' but its path.json declares slug 'something-else', the registry happily reports slug 'something-else'. The dir-name vs slug-field invariant the contract implies ('paths/<slug>/path.json') is unverified.",
      "fs.existsSync is the recommended-against probe — it returns false on ANY error (ENOENT, EACCES, broken symlink). On a permission-restricted path.json the registry will report 'missing-path-json' even though the file exists. Also, existsSync followed by readFileSync is a TOCTOU pattern (irrelevant in single-user CLI but still antipattern). Contract A7 names a 'malformed' / 'missing' distinction; conflating unreadable with missing breaks that distinction.",
      "registry.ts imports validatePath but never imports or invokes validatePhases. The contract names phases.json as a first-class shape contract (Files line for schemas/phases.ts, A5 + the contract behavior 'lists every well-formed path it discovers'), and a path is by definition phase-bearing content. Today a directory with a valid path.json but a corrupt or absent phases.json is reported as a healthy PathInfo. The schemas/phases.ts module is therefore dead code at the registry boundary — it only exists for direct test calls. This is an integration gap between two engine modules that were designed to compose.",
      "T-037/T-038/T-039 exercise validatePhases() in isolation, but no test wires phases.json through the registry. The current implementation never reads or validates phases.json — it only validates path.json. A path with a missing or schema-invalid phases.json (e.g. zero-spot phase) is happily surfaced in result.paths with no warning, and no test would catch this. The contract's 'schema-invalid files' clause for the registry is therefore only enforced for path.json. An implementer could ship a registry that completely ignores phases.json (as this one does) and pass green, even though contract.md/Files names phases.ts as a 'runtime validator for phases.json schema-only'."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Cycle 4 (the only consumer of phase semantics) will receive PathInfos that the engine vouched for, then crash when it tries to load phases. The 'parametricity' guarantee in A6 is weaker than advertised: dropping a path dir with a broken phases.json gets quiet acceptance instead of a structured warning. The contract's 'phases.json schema-only validation' obligation is not enforced anywhere observable.",
      "Cycle 2+ tools that resolve a slug back to a filesystem dir (e.g. to load phases or run a build_command) cannot rely on the slug to find the dir. Two paths with the same internal slug across different dirs would dedupe weirdly downstream. No current test catches this because T-019 fixture and T-020 fixture both have matching dir names.",
      "User-visible warning misidentifies the cause; debugging requires running stat manually. Not a green-test failure because no fixture exercises a permission-denied path.json.",
      "A future cycle (4) that consumes phases.json will either discover the malformed file at lesson-render time (late failure) or have to re-scan the directory itself, duplicating registry responsibility. Worse, downstream code can rely on the registry's surface as 'these paths are valid' when in reality only path.json was checked. The 'self-contained content' promise of paths/<slug>/ is broken because the engine doesn't enforce its own structural invariants.",
      "Phases-schema regressions are undetected at the registry level. A path with malformed phases.json will be advertised to learners and only blow up downstream in cycle 4 when phases are consumed."
    ],
