  {
    "cluster_id": "C002",
    "title": "scanRegistry conflates ENOENT with other readdir errors as 'no-paths-dir'",
    "file": "mcp/server/src/registry.ts",
    "line_ranges": [
      "27-39"
    ],
    "agreement_count": 2,
    "reviewers": [
      1,
      3
    ],
    "max_severity": "medium",
    "min_severity": "low",
    "disputed_severity": false,
    "categories": [
      "correctness",
      "error-handling"
    ],
    "recommendations": [
      "Inspect err.code: ENOENT → 'no-paths-dir'; ENOTDIR → 'paths-not-a-directory'; everything else → 'paths-read-error' with the underlying message. T-025 only exercises the ENOENT path so this is currently green by coincidence.",
      "Bind the error (catch (err)) and branch on err.code: ENOENT -> 'no-paths-dir'; ENOTDIR -> a new 'paths-not-a-directory' kind; EACCES -> 'paths-dir-unreadable'; otherwise a generic 'paths-dir-error' kind that includes err.message in the warning. Preserve the original message so the user can act on it."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "The catch block returns kind 'no-paths-dir' for ANY error from readdirSync — including EACCES (permission denied), ENOTDIR (path is a file), EMFILE (file table full). Only ENOENT semantically matches 'absent paths directory' per A9. A path that exists but is unreadable will be reported as absent, hiding the real cause from the user.",
      "The try/catch around fs.readdirSync uses an anonymous catch (no err binding) and unconditionally returns the 'no-paths-dir' warning. EACCES (permission denied), ENOTDIR (paths/ is a regular file), EMFILE/ENFILE (descriptor exhaustion), and ELOOP (symlink loop) all collapse to the same misleading 'Paths directory not found' message. The original error message is dropped entirely."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "User runs /sui-deepbook-course:start, sees 'no paths installed', and assumes they need to clone path content — when actually their paths/ dir has wrong permissions and is unreadable. Diagnosis loop is broken. The empty-paths-dir vs no-paths-dir distinction in A8/A9 was specifically introduced to make this discoverable; ENOENT-only handling preserves it.",
      "When a user's paths/ directory exists but is unreadable (chmod 000, owned by another user, replaced with a file), the start tool tells them the directory is missing. Diagnosis path is wrong; the user will look for a missing directory rather than fix the permissions or the misnamed file. Test T-025 only exercises the genuine ENOENT case, so this misclassification ships unobserved."
    ],
    "evidence": "} catch {\n    return {\n      paths: [],\n      warnings: [\n        {\n          kind: 'no-paths-dir',\n          message: `Paths directory not found: ${scanRoot}`,\n        },\n      ],\n    };\n  }",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "medium",
      "high"
    ],
    "source_ids": [
      "R1-003",
      "R3-001"
    ]
