    ],
    "max_severity": "medium",
    "min_severity": "low",
    "disputed_severity": false,
    "categories": [
      "design",
      "simplicity"
    ],
    "recommendations": [
      "Either (a) genuinely boot the MCP server: spawn `node dist/index.js` (or tsx) over stdio, connect a `Client` from `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/client/...`, and route callTool through it — then the harness has zero per-tool knowledge; or (b) re-use the same registration mechanism by having index.ts export a `registerTools(server)` factory that the harness can mount on an in-memory transport. Either way, remove the per-tool if-branch and the synthetic envelope.",
      "Either (a) actually spawn the MCP server via stdio and use the SDK's Client to call tools (a few extra lines, but matches the name), or (b) rename to `inProcessDispatcher` and drop the HarnessInstance/BootOptions ceremony — just export `callStart(projectRoot)` returning the same shape. The contract says 'boot the MCP server'; option (a) is the honest read."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "The harness's callTool dispatcher contains a literal `if (toolName === 'start')` branch that imports and calls runStart directly, then synthesizes an MCP-shaped { content: [{ type: 'text', text: JSON.stringify(...) }] } envelope. This means: (1) every future tool added in cycles 2–5 (preflight probe, lesson flow, etc.) requires editing harness.ts to add another if-branch — the harness has hard-coded knowledge of the tool registry that index.ts is supposed to own; (2) the harness never exercises the actual stdio transport, MCP framing, zod arg validation, or the server.tool registration in index.ts, so 'integration test' is misnamed — it's a thin wrapper around a direct function call. The contract (A12) says 'boots the MCP server'; this implementation does not boot the server.",
      "bootHarness is documented (contract A12) as 'boots the MCP server and successfully invokes start'. The implementation never instantiates McpServer, never connects a transport, and contains a single switch branch (`if (toolName === 'start')`) that calls runStart directly. The throw on unknown tool is unreachable in cycle 1 (start is the only tool registered). HarnessInstance interface, BootOptions interface, and the no-op shutdown() add ceremony around what is effectively a one-line wrapper over runStart."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Two coupled hazards. (a) Cycle 2 will add runPreflightProbe and the harness will need a parallel branch — drift between index.ts's registered tools and harness.ts's mock-dispatcher is silent until a scenario fires. (b) Real MCP transport bugs (zod schema mismatch, argument shape, JSON-RPC envelope) cannot be caught by future scenarios because the harness never speaks MCP. The integration claim in T-028 is weaker than the test name suggests.",
      "The harness misrepresents itself: tests think they exercise the MCP transport surface, but they bypass it entirely. Cycle 2-5 scenarios that depend on actual MCP wire behavior will need a rewrite. Today's complexity is also dishonest — the interfaces imply a non-trivial harness."
    ],
    "evidence": "if (toolName === 'start') {\n      const root = typeof args['projectRoot'] === 'string' ? args['projectRoot'] : projectRoot;\n      const result = await runStart({ projectRoot: root });",
