    "max_severity": "medium",
    "min_severity": "low",
    "disputed_severity": false,
    "categories": [
      "design"
    ],
    "recommendations": [
      "Replace the open shape with a tagged union, e.g. `type RegistryWarning = { kind: 'no-paths-dir'; message: string } | { kind: 'empty-paths-dir'; message: string } | { kind: 'missing-path-json'; message: string; dir: string } | { kind: 'malformed-path-json' | 'invalid-path-json'; message: string; path: string }`. Export the union from registry.ts so start.ts and skill renderers can re-export and exhaustive-check.",
      "Either `export type PathInfo = PathData` (or just re-export PathData as PathInfo) and `paths.push(validation.value)` directly, or drop PathInfo and have scanRegistry return `{ paths: PathData[]; warnings: ... }`. The personalization_options narrowing from `PersonalizationOption[]` to `string[]` in PathInfo is also lossy — re-using PathData preserves the literal-union typing for downstream consumers.",
      "Pick one. If the design wants async I/O (recommended for an MCP server), switch to `fs.promises.readdir`, `fs.promises.readFile`, `fs.promises.stat` — the existsSync check folds into a try/catch on stat or readFile. If sync is fine for cycle 1's tiny scan, drop `async` from the signature and return RegistryResult directly; let start.ts handle the lifting if it ever wants to parallelize."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "RegistryWarning declares `kind: string` and an open optional grab-bag of `path?: string` and `dir?: string`. The contract enumerates a closed set of warning kinds: 'no-paths-dir', 'empty-paths-dir', 'missing-path-json', 'malformed-path-json', 'invalid-path-json' (plus the phases-related ones if R2-001 is fixed). A discriminated union (kind: 'no-paths-dir' | 'empty-paths-dir' | ...) with per-kind required fields would let TypeScript catch a typo like 'malformed-paths-json' (note the trailing 's') at compile time and would let callers (skill renderer, future tools) exhaustively switch on kind. Right now any consumer that wants to format a warning has to defensively check both `path` and `dir` because the type system never tells them which one is set.",
      "registry.ts declares `PathInfo` with the exact same five fields as `PathData` in schemas/path.ts (slug, title, summary, personalization_options, build_command), then manually copies field-by-field in the closing `paths.push({ ... })`. This is shape duplication: any future field added to path.json must be added in three places (PathData, PathInfo, and the manual copy), and a typo in the copy block silently drops a field. The registry is the consumer of the schema's parsed value — that value should be the source of truth.",
      "scanRegistry is declared `async` and returns `Promise<RegistryResult>`, but every fs operation inside is synchronous: readdirSync, existsSync, readFileSync. The async signature is purely cosmetic and misleads callers (e.g. start.ts awaits it as if I/O is overlapped with probeOutputStyle, but it isn't). Either the design wants async I/O (use fs.promises) or the function should be sync and the signature should reflect that. The current state is the awkward middle: API surface promises async semantics, implementation delivers blocking I/O."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Encourages stringly-typed branching in downstream renderers (skills/course-engine, future tools) and silently allows the producer side to drift from the documented vocabulary. Hurts the 'engine extensibility without coupling' design goal: a new warning kind cannot be added in one place — the producer and every consumer pay the cost.",
      "Naming/abstraction-layer leak: the schema layer's job is to parse-and-validate into a typed value; the registry layer's job is to aggregate and warn. Today registry.ts re-encodes the row shape, which couples it to path.json's field set. Adding a new path.json field in cycle 4 will require touching registry.ts even though no registry behavior changes.",
      "Future cycles that assume the registry is non-blocking (e.g. running it concurrently with another probe in cycle 2) will be silently surprised — the event loop stalls during the directory walk. It's also a naming/contract leak: an async function that does no async work is a low-grade design smell that compounds when the surface grows."
    ],
    "evidence": "export async function scanRegistry(scanRoot: string): Promise<RegistryResult> {\n  let entries: fs.Dirent[];\n  try {\n    entries = fs.readdirSync(scanRoot, { withFileTypes: true });",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "high"
    ],
    "source_ids": [
      "R2-002",
      "R2-004",
      "R2-007"
    ]
