    "cluster_id": "C004",
    "title": "existsSync precheck on path.json invites TOCTOU and EACCES misclassification",
    "file": "mcp/server/src/registry.ts",
    "line_ranges": [
      "74-84",
      "63-71",
      "76-84"
    ],
    "agreement_count": 2,
    "reviewers": [
      3,
      6
    ],
    "max_severity": "low",
    "min_severity": "low",
    "disputed_severity": false,
    "categories": [
      "error-handling",
      "security"
    ],
    "recommendations": [
      "Use a distinct warning kind for read failures, e.g. 'unreadable-path-json', and reserve 'malformed-path-json' for JSON.parse failures only. Include err.code if available.",
      "Drop the existsSync precheck. Call fs.readFileSync inside the try/catch and branch on err.code in the catch: ENOENT -> 'missing-path-json'; EACCES -> 'unreadable-path-json'; default -> generic with err.message. Single source of truth and no race window.",
      "Either fs.lstat(pathJsonFile) and skip with a warning if isSymbolicLink() returns true, or fs.realpathSync and assert the resolved path starts with the canonicalized scanRoot. Given the trusted-dev-tool context this is genuinely low priority, but the check is a 5-line addition."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "When fs.readFileSync(pathJsonFile, ...) throws (EACCES on the file, EISDIR if path.json is a directory, etc.), the warning emitted has kind 'malformed-path-json'. The same kind is used for genuine JSON.parse failures a few lines later. A reader cannot distinguish 'I cannot read your file' from 'your file is not valid JSON'.",
      "fs.existsSync(pathJsonFile) is used to decide between emitting 'missing-path-json' and proceeding to readFileSync. existsSync returns false on EACCES (cannot stat the parent), so a permission-denied case reports as 'missing-path-json' even when the file is present. It also creates a TOCTOU window: the file may be deleted between existsSync and readFileSync, causing a different warning kind ('malformed-path-json' per the read-error path). The two warnings disagree on what is wrong.",
      "scanRegistry uses fs.readFileSync(pathJsonFile, 'utf8') where pathJsonFile is path.join(scanRoot, entry.name, 'path.json'). Although entry.name is a basename (no '../' traversal possible from a Dirent), path.json itself can be a symbolic link pointing anywhere on disk, including ~/.ssh/id_rsa or /etc/passwd. fs.readFileSync follows symlinks. There is no fs.realpath or stat check confirming the resolved target stays within scanRoot."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "The user is told their JSON is malformed and goes to lint/reformat it, when the real issue is filesystem. Diagnostic friction; not a correctness bug because the path is correctly skipped either way.",
      "Inconsistent diagnostics for the same underlying state, depending on race timing and permission setup. The cycle-1 surface is small enough that this is unlikely to bite, but it is a smell that compounds when registries grow.",
      "An attacker who can write a single file inside any paths/<slug>/ dir (i.e. anyone with repo-write access — already trusted) could place a symlink at path.json. The ensuing JSON.parse would fail and surface a 'malformed-path-json' warning containing the absolute path of the offending file (not its contents), so direct exfiltration is bounded. The realistic risk is denial-of-service via a symlink to /dev/zero or a multi-GB file, since there is no size cap before readFileSync (see R6-002)."
    ],
    "evidence": "    try {\n      raw = fs.readFileSync(pathJsonFile, 'utf8');\n    } catch (err) {\n      warnings.push({\n        kind: 'malformed-path-json',\n        message: `Failed to read ${pathJsonFile}: ${err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err)}`,\n        path: pathJsonFile,\n      });\n      continue;\n    }",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "high",
      "medium"
    ],
    "source_ids": [
      "R3-003",
      "R3-004",
      "R6-001"
    ]
